The Geometry of Non-Commutative Correlations:

From Deformation Quantization to Bell Polytopes

Author: Ouadi Maakoul
version : 3.1

---

Abstract

This thesis resolves the Einstein–Bohr debate through a geometric analysis of non‑commutative correlations. We demonstrate that the transition from classical determinism to quantum probabilism is encoded in the deformation of a commutative $C^*$-algebra into a non‑commutative one, with the parameter $\hbar$ governing the curvature of the resulting correlation set.

The core contribution is a four‑paper investigation establishing that quantum non‑locality is not a physical anomaly but a geometric consequence of non‑commutativity.

Paper 1 uses deformation quantization to prove that the leading quantum correction to the CHSH functional scales as $\hbar^2$ times an integral of the second‑order Moyal operator applied to the measured observables, linking Bell violation directly to the non‑commutative structure of phase space.

Paper 2 characterises the curved boundary of the quantum set $\mathcal{Q}$ for the $(3,3,2)$ scenario using the Navascués–Pironio–Acín hierarchy, proving the existence of boundary points not exposed by any linear functional and providing numerical evidence for curvature scaling.

Paper 3 derives state‑independent entropic inequalities that witness Kochen–Specker contextuality in qutrits, combining Maassen–Uffink uncertainty relations with sheaf‑theoretic methods to obtain robust experimental tests.

Paper 4 interprets quantum measurement as a geodesic projection in the space of density matrices, proving that the post‑measurement state maximises quantum relative entropy subject to outcome constraints, placing the collapse postulate on a firm information‑geometric foundation.

Together, these results establish that the classical polytope $\mathcal{L}$ emerges as the $\hbar\to0$ limit of the curved quantum set $\mathcal{Q}$, and that the "spooky action" of quantum mechanics is a manifestation of the curvature induced by non‑commutativity. This work bridges foundational questions in quantum theory with modern convex geometry and quantum information science.

