2.2 Deformation Quantization and the Moyal Product

2.2.1 Phase Space Geometry

Let $\mathcal{M} = \mathbb{R}^{2n}$ be the classical phase space with coordinates $(q,p) = (q_1,\ldots,q_n,p_1,\ldots,p_n)$ and symplectic form

\omega = \sum_{i=1}^n dq_i \wedge dp_i.

The Poisson bracket of two smooth functions $f,g \in C^\infty(\mathcal{M})$ is

\{f,g\} = \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{\partial f}{\partial q_i}\frac{\partial g}{\partial p_i} - \frac{\partial f}{\partial p_i}\frac{\partial g}{\partial q_i} \right).

2.2.2 Moyal Star Product

Deformation quantization seeks an associative but non‑commutative product $\star$ on $C^\infty(\mathcal{M})$ such that for $\hbar \to 0$,

f \star g = fg + O(\hbar), \quad f \star g - g \star f = i\hbar\{f,g\} + O(\hbar^3).

The Moyal star product is defined by

(f \star g)(x) = f(x) \, \exp\!\left( \frac{i\hbar}{2} \!\left( \overset{\leftarrow}{\partial}_q \cdot \overset{\rightarrow}{\partial}_p - \overset{\leftarrow}{\partial}_p \cdot \overset{\rightarrow}{\partial}_q \right) \right) g(x),

where the arrows indicate the direction in which the derivatives act. Expanding the exponential yields

f \star g = fg + \frac{i\hbar}{2}\{f,g\} + \frac{\hbar^2}{8} \Delta(f,g) + O(\hbar^4),

with

\Delta(f,g) = \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial q^2}\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial p^2} + \frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial p^2}\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial q^2} - 2\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial q\partial p}\frac{\partial^2 g}{\partial q\partial p}.

Theorem 2.5 (Associativity). The Moyal product is associative: $(f \star g) \star h = f \star (g \star h)$ for all smooth $f,g,h$.

Proof. The product corresponds to the composition of Weyl operators; associativity follows from the associativity of operator multiplication. Alternatively, one can verify directly using the integral representation. ∎

2.2.3 Weyl Quantization

The Weyl quantization map $\mathcal{W}$ sends a classical symbol $f$ to an operator on $L^2(\mathbb{R}^n)$ via

\mathcal{W}(f) = \frac{1}{(2\pi\hbar)^n} \int_{\mathbb{R}^{2n}} \tilde f(\xi)\, e^{i(\xi_q Q + \xi_p P)/\hbar}\, d^{2n}\xi,

where $[Q_j, P_k] = i\hbar \delta_{jk}$ and $\tilde f$ is the Fourier transform of $f$. This map satisfies

\mathcal{W}(f \star g) = \mathcal{W}(f)\mathcal{W}(g).

Thus the Moyal product on symbols corresponds exactly to operator multiplication.

