2.6 Contextuality and Sheaf‑Theoretic Methods

2.6.1 Kochen–Specker Contextuality

Contextuality generalises Bell non‑locality to scenarios where measurements are not necessarily space‑like separated. A contextuality scenario consists of a set of measurements $\mathcal{M}$ and a compatibility structure indicating which subsets of measurements can be performed jointly (called contexts). A non‑contextual hidden variable model assumes that each measurement has a predetermined outcome, independent of which compatible measurements are performed alongside it.

Formally, an empirical model assigns a probability distribution $P_{C}$ to each context $C$, representing the joint outcomes of the measurements in $C$. The model is non‑contextual if there exists a global probability distribution $P$ on all measurements such that $P_C$ is the marginal of $P$ for each context $C$.

2.6.2 Sheaf‑Theoretic Framework

The sheaf‑theoretic approach [Abramsky & Brandenburger 2011] treats empirical models as assignments of probabilities to measurement outcomes that are consistent on overlapping contexts. Non‑contextual models correspond to global sections of a certain presheaf. Contextuality is witnessed by the failure of such global sections to exist, which can be detected via linear inequalities (contextuality inequalities) or topological obstructions.

