2.7 Entropic Methods

2.7.1 Shannon Entropy

For a probability distribution $p = (p_1,\ldots,p_n)$, the Shannon entropy is $H(p) = -\sum_i p_i \log p_i$. For two jointly distributed random variables $X,Y$, the conditional entropy is $H(X|Y) = H(X,Y) - H(Y)$.

2.7.2 Maassen–Uffink Uncertainty Relation

For two observables $A$ and $B$ with eigenvectors $|a_i\rangle$, $|b_j\rangle$, the Maassen–Uffink entropic uncertainty relation [Maassen & Uffink 1988] states:

H(A) + H(B) \ge -\log \max_{i,j} |\langle a_i | b_j \rangle|^2,

where $H(A)$ is the Shannon entropy of the measurement outcomes of $A$ in a given state. For mutually unbiased bases in dimension $d$, the bound becomes $H(A)+H(B) \ge \log d$.

2.7.3 Entropic Contextuality

Entropic inequalities can also witness contextuality. For the qutrit Kochen–Specker scenario with three mutually unbiased bases, one has the non‑contextual bound [Kurzynski 2012]

H(A|B) + H(B|C) + H(C|A) \ge \log\frac{9}{4},

while quantum mechanics allows $H(A|B)+H(B|C)+H(C|A) = \log\frac{3}{2}$ for any state.

