Appendix A: Detailed Calculations for Paper 1

A.1 Covariance Matrix of TMSV

The two‑mode squeezing operator $\hat{S}_{AB}(r) = \exp\!\big( r(\hat{a}\hat{b} - \hat{a}^\dagger \hat{b}^\dagger) \big)$ acts on annihilation operators as

\hat{S}_{AB}^\dagger(r) \hat{a} \hat{S}_{AB}(r) = \hat{a}\cosh r + \hat{b}^\dagger \sinh r,

\hat{S}_{AB}^\dagger(r) \hat{b} \hat{S}_{AB}(r) = \hat{b}\cosh r + \hat{a}^\dagger \sinh r.

In the quadrature basis $\hat{\mathbf{R}} = (\hat{q}_A, \hat{p}_A, \hat{q}_B, \hat{p}_B)^T$, with

\hat{q} = \sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2}}(\hat{a}+\hat{a}^\dagger),\quad \hat{p} = -i\sqrt{\frac{\hbar}{2}}(\hat{a}-\hat{a}^\dagger),

the covariance matrix $\Sigma_{ij} = \frac{1}{2}\langle \hat{R}_i\hat{R}_j + \hat{R}_j\hat{R}_i \rangle$ for the TMSV vacuum is

\Sigma = \frac{\hbar}{2} \begin{pmatrix}
\cosh(2r) & 0 & \sinh(2r) & 0 \\
0 & \cosh(2r) & 0 & -\sinh(2r) \\
\sinh(2r) & 0 & \cosh(2r) & 0 \\
0 & -\sinh(2r) & 0 & \cosh(2r)
\end{pmatrix}.

A.2 Gaussian Integration for $E(\alpha,\beta)$

We start from

E(\alpha,\beta) = \int \frac{d^2\lambda_A}{\pi} \frac{d^2\lambda_B}{\pi} e^{\alpha\lambda_A^* - \alpha^*\lambda_A} e^{\beta\lambda_B^* - \beta^*\lambda_B} \chi(\lambda_A, \lambda_B),

with

\chi(\lambda_A, \lambda_B) = \exp\!\left( -\frac{1}{2} \Big[ (|\lambda_A|^2 + |\lambda_B|^2) \cosh(2r) + (\lambda_A \lambda_B + \lambda_A^* \lambda_B^*) \sinh(2r) \Big] \right).

Write $\lambda_A = x_A + iy_A$, $\lambda_B = x_B + iy_B$, and similarly for $\alpha,\beta$. The exponent is a quadratic form in the four real variables. Completing the square yields

E(\alpha,\beta) = \frac{1}{\cosh(2r)} \exp\!\left( -2|\alpha|^2 - 2|\beta|^2 + 2\tanh(2r)(\alpha\beta + \alpha^*\beta^*) \right).

The factor $1/\cosh(2r)$ comes from the determinant of the quadratic form; the cross‑term arises from the off‑diagonal part.

A.3 Regularisation of the Parity Symbol

The Wigner symbol of the parity operator $\hat{\Pi}$ is $\pi\hbar \delta(q)\delta(p)$. This distributional symbol is not suitable for Moyal expansion. We regularise by convolving with a Gaussian of width $\sqrt{\epsilon}$:

W_{\hat{\Pi}_\epsilon}(q,p) = \frac{1}{\pi\hbar} \int e^{-\epsilon|\gamma|^2} e^{-i(\gamma_q q + \gamma_p p)/\hbar} d^2\gamma = \frac{1}{\epsilon} e^{-(q^2+p^2)/(\epsilon\hbar)}.

Choosing $\epsilon \sim \hbar$ ensures that the regularised symbol is smooth and that the error introduced is of order $\hbar^2$ in expectation values. The displaced regularised symbol is then a Gaussian centred at $\alpha$, with width $\sim \sqrt{\hbar}$.

