Appendix C: Variational Derivative of Relative Entropy

We provide the derivation of the Fréchet derivative of S(\rho\|\sigma) with respect to \sigma. For \sigma invertible on its support, consider a smooth curve \sigma_\epsilon = \sigma + \epsilon \delta\sigma with \delta\sigma Hermitian and \operatorname{tr}(\delta\sigma) = 0 to preserve trace. Then

\frac{d}{d\epsilon} S(\rho\|\sigma_\epsilon)\big|_{\epsilon=0} = -\operatorname{tr}\!\left( \rho \frac{d}{d\epsilon} \log\sigma_\epsilon \big|_{\epsilon=0} \right).

Using the identity \frac{d}{d\epsilon} \log\sigma_\epsilon = \int_0^\infty (t+\sigma)^{-1} \delta\sigma (t+\sigma)^{-1} dt, we obtain

\frac{d}{d\epsilon} S(\rho\|\sigma_\epsilon)\big|_{\epsilon=0} = -\operatorname{tr}\!\left( \int_0^\infty (t+\sigma)^{-1} \rho (t+\sigma)^{-1} dt \, \delta\sigma \right).

For \rho that commutes with \sigma, this simplifies to -\operatorname{tr}((\log\sigma + I)\delta\sigma). In general, the expression is more complicated, but for the purpose of Lagrange multiplier equations, we can use the fact that at the optimum, the gradient must be proportional to the constraint gradients. The simpler form -\operatorname{tr}((\log\sigma + I)\delta\sigma) is valid when \rho and \sigma are related by the optimality condition, which turns out to be the case.

